+
+# Why CVE-2025-15079 in `curl` / `libcurl` Is a False Positive on Debian Bookworm
+
+## Overview: What Is This CVE?
+
+**CVE-2025-15079** is a vulnerability in **libcurl** when doing SSH-based transfers (SCP or SFTP) with a **user-specified known_hosts file**. When curl is built with the **libssh** backend, libssh can fall back to its **global** known_hosts file (path set at build time) if a host is not found in the specified file. libcurl did not prevent this fallback, so it could accept connections to hosts that were only in the global file, bypassing the intended restriction.
+
+Security scanners (e.g., Trivy, Grype, Snyk) may report this CVE when they see **curl** or **libcurl** in Debian Bookworm. This document explains in detail why **Debian Bookworm's curl/libcurl is not actually vulnerable** and why the finding should be treated as a **false positive**.
+
+---
+
+## CVE-2025-15079 – Technical Breakdown
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|--------|
+| **CVE** | CVE-2025-15079 |
+| **Title** | libssh global known_hosts override |
+| **Component** | curl / libcurl (SSH/SCP/SFTP via **libssh** backend only) |
+| **CWE** | CWE-297: Improper Validation of Certificate with Host Mismatch |
+| **Upstream severity** | Low |
+| **Introduced in** | curl **7.58.0** |
+| **Fixed in** | curl **8.18.0** (released 2026-01-07) |
+
+### Conditions Required for the Vulnerability to Apply
+
+The issue **only** applies when **all** of the following are true:
+
+1. **curl is built with the libssh backend** (not libssh2). The flaw is in how libcurl uses **libssh's** known_hosts API and its global fallback.
+2. The user performs **SCP or SFTP** transfers and sets a known_hosts file.
+3. curl version is in the affected range **7.58.0 through 8.17.0**.
+
+The official curl advisory states explicitly:
+
+> **This flaw only exists when libcurl is built to use the libssh backend, not the libssh2 based one.**
+
+curl selects **one** SSH backend at **build-time** (libssh, libssh2, or wolfSSH). If the build uses **libssh2**, the vulnerable libssh code path is not compiled or used.
+
+If any of these conditions is false, the vulnerability **cannot be triggered**.
+
+---
+
+## Why Debian Bookworm Is Not Vulnerable
+
+### 1. Build Configuration: Debian Uses libssh2, Not libssh
+
+The vulnerability **only** applies when curl is built with the **libssh** SSH backend. Debian's curl package is built with **libssh2** (on Debian) or **libssh** (on Ubuntu only), and on **Debian** the libssh backend is explicitly disabled.
+
+#### Evidence from Debian package source (curl 7.88.1-10+deb12u14, Bookworm)
+
+In **`debian/rules`**, the SSH backend is set explicitly:
+
+```makefile
+# disable libssh2 on Ubuntu (see #888449)
+ifeq ($(shell dpkg-vendor --derives-from Ubuntu && echo yes),yes)
+	CONFIGURE_ARGS += --with-libssh --without-libssh2
+else
+	CONFIGURE_ARGS += --without-libssh --with-libssh2
+endif
+```
+
+So on **Debian** (including Bookworm): `--without-libssh --with-libssh2` → SSH backend is **libssh2 only**. The **libssh** backend is **not** built. There is no code path that uses libssh's global known_hosts behaviour.
+
+| Source | URL |
+|--------|-----|
+| debian/rules | [sources.debian.org/src/curl/7.88.1-10+deb12u14/debian/rules](https://sources.debian.org/src/curl/7.88.1-10+deb12u14/debian/rules/) |
+| debian/control | [sources.debian.org/src/curl/7.88.1-10+deb12u14/debian/control](https://sources.debian.org/src/curl/7.88.1-10+deb12u14/debian/control/) |
+
+The **Debian Security Tracker** also states for CVE-2025-15079:
+
+> **Notes:** … **Debian builds with libssh2 for SSH backend**
+
+So the condition for the vulnerability (curl built with **libssh**) is **not met** on Debian. The vulnerable code path is **not used** in Debian's build.
+
+---
+
+### 2. Version (for completeness)
+
+**Debian Bookworm** ships **curl 7.88.1** (source package version `7.88.1-10+deb12u14`). The upstream affected range is **7.58.0 through 8.17.0**, so Bookworm's version is in that range. The reason Bookworm is not vulnerable is **not** the version but the **build configuration**: without the libssh backend, the flaw cannot be triggered.
+
+---
+
+## Summary Table: Debian Bookworm vs CVE-2025-15079
+
+| Check | Result |
+|-------|--------|
+| **Debian Bookworm curl version** | 7.88.1 |
+| **Affected version range (upstream)** | 7.58.0 – 8.17.0 (when built with **libssh**) |
+| **Is Bookworm curl built with libssh?** | **No** (`debian/rules`: `--without-libssh --with-libssh2` on Debian) |
+| **SSH backend in Debian Bookworm** | **libssh2** |
+| **Can this CVE be triggered on Bookworm?** | **No** |
+| **Conclusion** | **False positive** – no patch required for this CVE on Debian Bookworm |
+
+---
+
+## Recommendation for Scanners and Audits
+
+- **Treat CVE-2025-15079 as a false positive** for **Debian Bookworm**'s curl and libcurl packages.
+- **No code or package update is required** for this CVE on Bookworm; the vulnerable libssh backend is not used.
+- If your policy or scanner cannot mark it as a false positive, this document and the Debian package source (`debian/rules`) can be used as **evidence**.
+
+---
+
+## References
