+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,123 @@
+# Why CVE-2024-2379 in `curl` / `libcurl` Is a False Positive on Debian Bookworm
+
+## Overview: What Is This CVE?
+
+**CVE-2024-2379** is a vulnerability in **libcurl** that can cause **certificate verification to be skipped** for **QUIC (HTTP/3)** connections under specific conditions when curl is **built with wolfSSL**. The official description states:
+
+> libcurl skips the certificate verification for a QUIC connection under certain conditions, when built to use wolfSSL. If told to use an unknown/bad cipher or curve, the error path accidentally skips the verification and returns OK, thus ignoring any certificate problems.
+
+Security scanners (e.g., Trivy, Grype, Snyk) may report this CVE when they see **curl** or **libcurl** in Debian Bookworm. This document explains in detail why **Debian Bookworm’s curl/libcurl is not actually vulnerable** and why the finding should be treated as a **false positive**.
+
+---
+
+## CVE-2024-2379 – Technical Breakdown
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|--------|
+| **CVE** | CVE-2024-2379 |
+| **Title** | QUIC certificate check bypass with wolfSSL |
+| **Component** | curl / libcurl (QUIC + wolfSSL code path) |
+| **CWE** | CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation |
+| **Upstream severity** | Low |
+| **Introduced in** | curl **8.6.0** only (commit in 8.6.0 release) |
+| **Fixed in** | curl **8.7.0** (released 2024-03-27) |
+
+### Conditions Required for the Vulnerability to Apply
+
+The issue is only relevant when **all** of the following are true:
+
+1. **curl is built with wolfSSL** as the TLS backend (not OpenSSL, GnuTLS, or NSS).
+2. **wolfSSL** is built with the **`OPENSSL_COMPATIBLE_DEFAULTS`** symbol set (the curl project notes this is **not** set for the recommended `configure --enable-curl` builds).
+3. The **vulnerable code path** exists: it was **introduced in curl 8.6.0** and **fixed in 8.7.0**. Only the single version **8.6.0** is affected.
+
+If any of these conditions is false, the vulnerability **cannot be triggered**.
+
+---
+
+## Why Debian Bookworm Is Not Vulnerable
+
+### 1. Version: The Vulnerable Code Is Not Present
+
+Official curl security documentation states:
+
+- **Not affected:** curl **&lt; 8.6.0** and curl **≥ 8.7.0**
+- **Affected:** **Only curl 8.6.0**
+
+| Source | Statement |
+|--------|-----------|
+| [curl.se/docs/CVE-2024-2379.html](https://curl.se/docs/CVE-2024-2379.html) | *"Not affected versions: curl &lt; 8.6.0 and ≥ 8.7.0"* |
+| [curl.se/docs/vuln-8.6.0.html](https://curl.se/docs/vuln-8.6.0.html) | *"QUIC certificate check bypass with wolfSSL … From 8.6.0 … To and including 8.6.0"* |
+
+**Debian Bookworm** ships **curl 7.88.1** (source package version `7.88.1-10+deb12u14`).
+
+- **7.88.1** is **strictly less than 8.6.0** (different major version line: 7.x vs 8.x).
+- The bug was **introduced** in the 8.6.0 release; it does **not** exist in 7.x.
+- Therefore, **the vulnerable code path is not present** in Bookworm’s curl at all.
+
+So by **version alone**, Debian Bookworm is **not in the affected range**.
+
+---
+
+### 2. Build Configuration: Debian Does Not Use wolfSSL
+
+Even if the version were in the affected range, the issue **only** applies when curl is built with **wolfSSL**.
+
+Debian’s curl package in Bookworm is built with **three TLS backends**, none of which is wolfSSL:
+
+| Binary package | TLS backend |
+|----------------|-------------|
+| **libcurl4** | **OpenSSL** |
+| **libcurl3-gnutls** | **GnuTLS** |
+| **libcurl3-nss** | **NSS** |
+
+There is **no** `libcurl-wolfssl` or wolfSSL-based curl package in Debian Bookworm.
+
+The **Debian Security Tracker** explicitly documents this for CVE-2024-2379:
+
+> **Notes:** … **curl in Debian not built with wolfSSL support**
+
+So the **second condition** (curl built with wolfSSL) is **not met** on Debian. The vulnerability **cannot be triggered** on Debian’s build, regardless of version.
+
+---
+
+### 3. How the Tracker Presents This CVE
+
+On the [Debian Security Tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2024-2379), CVE-2024-2379 is listed under **"Open unimportant issues"** for the curl package. Bookworm may still appear in the “Vulnerable and fixed packages” table because the tracker often marks any release that has not reached the “fixed” upstream version (8.7.0+) as “vulnerable” from a **version** perspective. The tracker **notes** clarify the real situation:
+
+- **Introduced in:** curl 8.6.0  
+- **Fixed in:** curl 8.7.0  
+- **curl in Debian not built with wolfSSL support**
+
+So the **actionable** conclusion from Debian is: this is an **unimportant** issue for Debian’s curl because the vulnerable code and/or the required build configuration are not present.
+
+---
+
+## Summary Table: Debian Bookworm vs CVE-2024-2379
+
+| Check | Result |
+|-------|--------|
+| **Debian Bookworm curl version** | 7.88.1 |
+| **Affected version range (upstream)** | Only 8.6.0 |
+| **Is 7.88.1 in affected range?** | **No** (7.88.1 &lt; 8.6.0) |
+| **Is vulnerable code present in 7.88.1?** | **No** (introduced in 8.6.0) |
+| **Is Bookworm curl built with wolfSSL?** | **No** (OpenSSL / GnuTLS / NSS only) |
+| **Can this CVE be triggered on Bookworm?** | **No** |
+| **Conclusion** | **False positive** – no patch required for this CVE on Debian Bookworm |
+
+---
+
+## Recommendation for Scanners and Audits
+
+- **Treat CVE-2024-2379 as a false positive** for **Debian Bookworm**’s curl and libcurl packages.
+- **No code or package update is required** for this CVE on Bookworm; the issue is neither present in the shipped version nor in the build configuration.
+- If your policy or scanner cannot mark it as a false positive, this document can be used as **evidence** (version 7.88.1, no wolfSSL build, and upstream “not affected” for &lt; 8.6.0).
+
+---
+
